@real-or-random: Thank you for the history review. It's a shame that a few edge cases had to ruin it for everyone. I do have to wonder if the issues you mentioned were due to Autotools not being used correctly, but I guess that ship has sailed.

My interest comes not as a user but as a packager. Gentoo takes a purist approach to open-source software: anything than can be rebuilt from sources ought to be. Standard operating procedure is to discard pregenerated assets and rebuild them from sources wherever possible. This is what the ebuilds for libsecp256k1 do with the precomputed ecmult tables. We have had to employ a [hack](https://gitlab.com/bitcoin/gentoo/-/blob/d783d4d95cc1e7befeecec30a2d1f9e0d3a5ad72/dev-libs/libsecp256k1/libsecp256k1-0.1_pre20211216.ebuild#L75-84) to support cross-compiling, whereas most software packages that use Autotools and that compile tools to be executed during the build apparently have no trouble using `AX_PROG_CC_FOR_BUILD`.

I'll withdraw my request for proper cross-compilation support and continue carrying my patch downstream. Thank you for your time and explanation.
